TITLE: Ben Bernanke among 3 American winners of Nobel Prize in economics
SUMMARY: Former Federal Reserve chairman Ben Bernanke and two academic economists — Douglas Diamond and Philip Dybvig — share this year's Nobel Prize in economics for their work on bank runs.

TITLE: 3 economists win Nobel Prize in economic sciences for work on banks, financial crises
SUMMARY: The Nobel panel at the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences in Stockholm has announced the winners for the Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences are Ben Bernanke, Douglas Diamond and Philip Dybvig.

TITLE: For Chileans blinded in police violence, making music has become one path to healing
SUMMARY: All members of Hacía la Victoria ("Onward to Victory") sustained eye injuries during clashes with police in anti-government protests in 2019. Their lyrics focus on police brutality and their own pain.

TITLE: How Harris is listening — and speaking — about abortion rights before the midterms
SUMMARY: Vice President Harris has held more than 20 events on abortion rights since May. She's been traveling the country to listen and speak about what's become a top issue for Democratic voters.

TITLE: Harvey Weinstein faces his next criminal trial in Los Angeles this week
SUMMARY: Weinstein, a former Hollywood producer, is already serving his 23 year prison sentence doled out by a New York criminal court two years ago.

TITLE: Artificial intelligence could soon diagnose illness based on the sound of your voice
SUMMARY: Everything from your vocal cord vibrations to breathing patterns when you speak offers potential information about your health. Researchers are collecting voice data to one day use in an app.

TITLE: North Korea confirms a simulated use of nukes to 'wipe out' its enemies
SUMMARY: North Korea's recent barrage of missile launches were the simulated use of its tactical battlefield nuclear weapons to "wipe out" potential South Korean and U.S. targets, state media reported Monday

TITLE: Deadly missile strikes hit Kyiv as explosions reported in other cities across Ukraine
SUMMARY: Explosions on Monday rocked multiple cities across Ukraine, including deadly missile strikes on the capital Kyiv for the first time in months.

TITLE: A rain-fueled landslide sweeps through Venezuela town, leaving more than 20 dead
SUMMARY: A landslide fueled by flooding and days of torrential rain swept through a town in central Venezuela, leaving at least 22 people dead, authorities said Sunday.

TITLE: Power is back at Europe's largest nuclear plant. IAEA warns the situation can't last
SUMMARY: The Zaporizhzhia nuclear power plant in Ukraine went offline over the weekend after Russian shelling damaged the last remaining outside power source.

TITLE: Emily Sisson sets a record for American women at the Chicago Marathon
SUMMARY: Benson Kipruto of Kenya was first in the men's division while Ruth Chepngetich, also of Kenya, led the women's division. Sisson finished second.

TITLE: Putin calls the attack on a key bridge to Crimea a terrorist act
SUMMARY: The Russian president accused Ukrainian special services of carrying out an attack on the Kerch Bridge, a key supply line for Russian forces.

TITLE: An act of sabotage shut down parts of Germany's rail system for hours this weekend
SUMMARY: Officials say a key train communications system was compromised, stranding passenger and cargo trains across the northwest of the country on Saturday.

TITLE: First, a bridge strategic to Russia was attacked — then came the Ukrainian memes
SUMMARY: Ukrainians celebrated the Saturday attack on a key bridge connecting the Crimean peninsula to mainland Russia by flooding social media with memes, which have become a staple of the conflict.

TITLE: Ye takes to Twitter after Instagram restricts his account following antisemitic posts
SUMMARY: Ye, the rapper and fashion designer formerly known as Kanye West, had recently accused hip hop mogul Diddy of being under the influence of "the Jewish people."
